\begin_layout Section
The Political Economy Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal is to present a simplified model of the political economy approach.
 The idea of this theory is that there is a political mechanism of income
 redistribution.
 Too much inequality leads to political pressures to increase taxes on the
 rich.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The big question with inequality and growth is how to test it empirically
 (results are not random and hard to isolate).
 A country might have high inequality, caused by high 
\series bold
heterogeneity
\series default
 - which leads to a correlation, but not to a causal effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
One Period Endowment Economy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cumulative distribution of (pre-tax) wealth is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(x)=\begin{cases}
0 & x<0\\{}
[\alpha/(1+\alpha)]^{\alpha}x^{\alpha} & x\in[0,(1+\alpha)/\alpha]\\
1 & x>(1+\alpha)/\alpha
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1]$
\end_inset

 impacts the inequality level of the economy.
 Then the density function is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
0 & x<0\\
\alpha\left(\frac{\alpha}{1+\alpha}\right)^{\alpha}x^{\alpha-1} & x\in[0,(1+\alpha)/\alpha]\\
0 & x>(1+\alpha)/\alpha
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measures equality, and increasing it makes the distribution more equal.
 Increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 make the rich less rich, and the poor less poor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean income is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{x}=\int_{0}^{(1+\alpha)/\alpha}xf(x)dx=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The median income is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(m)=1/2
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing the median to the average captures the inequality.
 The median is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

typical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 income, while the average it pulled up by the rich.
 Dividing the median by the average provides some indication on the level
 of inequality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variance is yet another indicator - it is decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Redistribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tax can be 0 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (fraction of wealth taxes and redistributed).
 The income of individual 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{x}^{i}=(1=\tau)x^{i}+\tau\theta\bar{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\theta<1$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
distortionary
\series default
 taxation (which is the popular approach - the government is inefficient),
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>1$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
beneficial
\series default
 taxation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An agent would prefer redistribution if:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{x}^{i}>x^{i}\leftrightarrow\theta\bar{x}>x_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=1$
\end_inset

 it means:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{x}^{i}>x^{i}\leftrightarrow\bar{x}>x^{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(the individual has less than average income).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even when the government is extremely inefficient (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0.5$
\end_inset

), there are people who benefit from it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}=1$
\end_inset

, redistribution is beneficial for an individual who has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{x}^{i}>x^{i}\leftrightarrow\theta>x^{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
redistribution is supported by a fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\theta)$
\end_inset

 of the population:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(\theta)=\begin{cases}
0 & \theta<0\\{}
[\alpha/(1+\alpha)]^{\alpha}\theta^{\alpha} & \theta\in[0,(1+\alpha)/\alpha]\\
1 & \theta>(1+\alpha)/\alpha
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
F(\theta)=1 & \alpha\rightarrow0\\
\partial F(\theta)/\partial\alpha<0 & \alpha\in(0,1]\\
F(\theta)=\theta/2 & \alpha=1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 declines, more and more people are pushed towards low income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>1$
\end_inset

, there is more support for taxation at high incomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the rich become richer, they oppose taxation.
 An average person wants good public services, while the average 
\series bold
rich
\series default
 person would not care about that, and only rely on the private sector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The more you push people down, the more they are supportive of taxation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 But then, some people are pushed up - and the rich become more hostile.
 There are opposite effects: pushing down (people are in favor of redistribution
), pushing up (people oppose it).
 Therefore, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>1$
\end_inset

 the effect is 
\series bold
not
\series default
 monotonic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When there is more support for taxes, the compromise would be higher taxation.
\end_layout

